<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-279-738  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 279 738.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 19 1990 v9 n6 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Defense plan would control unwieldy growth of software. (theDepartment of Defense Software Master Plan)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyMilitaryNational GovernmentSoftware PackagesSoftware SelectionManagement of EDPSoftware MaintenanceEquipment AcquisitionPlanningUnited States. Department of Defense.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Defense Plan Would Control Unwieldy Growth of SoftwareandM;Under a draft plan released last month, the Defense Department would mergeoversight of software policies and acquisition into one office.andM;The DOD Software Master Plan would consolidate all software policies andacquisitions into a new division under John Betti, the undersecretary foracquisition.andP;  The move would give DOD officials more control over theunwieldy growth of software throughout the department, according to the draftreport from a Defense Acquisition Board committee.andM;The plan would help reduce the costs of software development and life cyclemaintenance, the report said.andP;  The plan also would improve the research,development, testing and deployment of software systems, includingmission-critical computer systems, automated information systems and weaponssystems, the report said.andM;The department treats mission-critical systems and MIS as separate kinds ofprograms, with different policies and procedures.andM;&quot;The current dual oversight process for software sensitive systems isinadequate for modern defense systems and has resulted in duplicative,conflicting and artificially fragmented acquisition guidance, policies andoversight for software sensitive systems,&quot; the report said.andM;The new software office also would coordinate DOD's efforts to develop andpromote the use of Ada.andM;The Software Master Plan was developed by a working group of the DAB'sScience and Technology Committee.andM;Last July, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney merged the former DOD MajorAutomated Information Systems Review Council with the Defense AcquisitionBoard (DAB).andP;  The newly named Major Automated Information Systems ReviewCommittee, or MAISRC, is now a subgroup of the DAB, which overseesmission-critical systems.andP;  Betti heads the DAB.andM;The deadline for comments on the draft is April 6.andP;  Atwood will decide how toproceed after he reviews the comments.andO;</TEXT></DOC>